==English==

===Etymology===
Alternation (due to {{m|en|give}}) of {{inh|en|enm|forȝiven}}, {{m|enm|foryiven}}, from {{inh|en|ang|forġiefan|t=to forgive, give up, provide}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*fragebaną|t=to give away; give up; release; forgive}}, {{prefix|en|for|give}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|forgeve}}, {{m|sco|forgif}}, {{m|sco|forgie||to forgive}}, {{cog|fy|ferjaan||to forgive}}, {{cog|nl|vergeven||to forgive}}, {{cog|de|vergeben||to forgive}}, {{cog|is|fyrirgefa||to forgive}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|fər-gĭv', fôr-gĭv'}}, {{IPA|/fə(ɹ)ˈɡɪv/|/fɔː(ɹ)ˈɡɪv/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-forgive.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɪv|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|forgives|forgiving|forgave|forgiven}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[pardon]], to waive any negative feeling or desire for punishment.
#: '''''Forgive''' others, not because they deserve forgiveness, but because you deserve peace.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[accord]] [[forgiveness]].
#: ''Only the brave know how to '''forgive'''...A coward never '''forgave'''; it is not in his nature.'' - [[q: Laurence Sterne|Laurence Sterne]]

